# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 16:10:19
<overview>
<p>The Condor-class DropShip is one of the largest vessels designed specifically for infantry transport, capable of delivering a full battalion of 336 troops along with twenty light support vehicles directly onto the battlefield. Entering service in 2801 during the opening years of the First Succession War, the Condor was built as a military aerodyne with unusually robust wing structures that proved far less susceptible to control surface damage than those of comparable designs. The vessel earned a strong reputation among infantry commanders for its spacious troop accommodations, well-equipped onboard medical facilities, and substantial cargo capacity, making it one of the most valued dedicated infantry transports in the Inner Sphere. Its distinctive broad-winged silhouette became a familiar sight above contested landing zones throughout the Succession Wars and beyond, and the design has since spawned both a hospital ship conversion and a civilian cargo variant, testament to the fundamental soundness of the original airframe.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Condor's interior is organized across four decks accessed through a large aft door ramp that opens into an infantry-ready staging area. An oversized cargo elevator connects the ramp to the second deck, which houses mess and recreation facilities alongside a large training area and unusually spacious barracks-style quarters for the infantry complement. Two main cargo holds, one on each side of the fuselage, can accommodate over 750 tons of supplies each, while twenty light vehicle berths provide transport for the battalion's organic support assets.</p><p>The third deck mirrors the second in general layout, though the training area and some barracks give way to a well-equipped medical facility capable of treating six emergency cases simultaneously, with converted barracks serving as a small recovery ward. The uppermost deck contains crew and command facilities, the main computer systems, and a small lounge and conference area for the battalion staff. The compact bridge uses a cockpit-like tandem seating arrangement, accessed through a narrow hallway running between the fire control and communications stations. The Condor's wings are heavily braced with structural supports and contain fuel bunkers, weapon bays, and landing gear, along with considerable hidden space accessible via internal passageways.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The original Condor serves as the primary infantry transport in every Successor State military, forming the backbone of planetary assault infantry operations throughout the Inner Sphere. The vessel is typically deployed as part of larger landing forces, delivering its battalion-strength complement alongside armored and BattleMech formations carried by other DropShips. Condor crews have long been known for their resourcefulness, making extensive use of the undesignated wing cavities for unofficial cargo storage during extended deployments far from established supply lines. The design's proven reliability and durable airframe construction have kept many original-production Condors in active frontline service for decades, with some vessels accumulating impressive service records spanning multiple conflicts.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Condor entered service in 2801, early in the First Succession War, when the need for dedicated infantry transports capable of large-scale planetary assault operations became acute. The design's emphasis on troop comfort and medical capability reflected hard-won lessons from the Star League era about the importance of delivering infantry forces in fighting condition rather than merely ferrying bodies between worlds. The robust wing design, with its heavy structural bracing and integrated fuel bunkers, proved remarkably durable in combat conditions.</p><p>Throughout the Succession Wars, the Condor served in the fleets of every Great House, becoming a standard component of planetary assault forces wherever infantry operations were planned. The vessel's unique wing cavities, containing large amounts of accessible but undesignated space, became an open secret among Condor crews, who used these hidden areas to store additional equipment and supplies beyond the vessel's official manifest. This unofficial cargo capacity proved invaluable during extended campaigns where supply lines were uncertain.</p><p>The years following the Fourth Succession War saw two significant developments for the Condor class. Beginning in 3035, approximately two dozen vessels were converted into hospital ships, their cargo bays replaced with treatment wards and their operating theaters greatly expanded. These converted vessels, nicknamed Doves, became prized assets in every fleet that operated them. ComStar acquired the largest share, fielding twelve Doves, with the remainder distributed among the Successor State navies.</p><p>In 3054, Nimakachi Fusion Products Limited began production of an upgraded Condor featuring recovered Star League-era weapons technology. Early production models suffered from electromagnetic interference between the nose-mounted weapons systems, but models produced after late 3055 incorporated a redesigned coolant circuit that resolved the issue. The upgraded design slightly reduced cargo capacity in exchange for improved range and firepower.</p><p>By 3079, Nimakachi had introduced the Stork, a purpose-built civilian cargo variant of the Condor produced at their Dalton facility. The Stork represented a significant departure from the military-focused lineage of the Condor family, leveraging the design's proven airframe for commercial applications in the post-Jihad reconstruction era.</p>
</history>

